-- Medtronic, Monsanto, Warner Music, Coach, Eaton: Intellectual Property
-- Victoria Slind-Flor
-- 2010-07-01T11:01:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-01/medtronic-monsanto-warner-music-coach-eaton-intellectual-property.html

          
          
             Medtronic Inc. ’s CoreValve unit
didn’t infringe  Edwards Lifesciences Corp. ’s European patent for
artificial heart-valve technology, a U.K. appeals court ruled.  
 A panel of three judges at the Court of Appeal in London
yesterday upheld a January 2009 trial-court ruling that
determined Edwards’s patent was “valid, but not infringed.”  
 “Following argument, we were able to form a clear
conclusion to the effect that the CoreValve product did not
infringe,” Judge Robin Jacob said in the ruling.  
 Edwards sued Irvine, California-based CoreValve over an
invention for  valve replacement  using blood-vessel catheters,
without open-heart surgery. Minneapolis-based Medtronic acquired
CoreValve in April 2009 for $700 million, after the dispute with
Edwards had already started.  
 “The ruling has no effect on sales” of the Edwards’
Sapien heart valves “in the U.K. or any other country,”
Edwards spokesman Michael George said yesterday in an e-mail.  
 In April, a U.S. jury in Wilmington, Delaware, awarded
Edwards $73 million in damages for infringing a U.S. patent for
the same technology. Medtronic in February said a German appeals
court ruled that the CoreValve system didn’t infringe a related
patent in that country.  
 The lower court rejected Medtronic’s claim that the Edwards
patent is invalid. The appeal court let that finding stand and
didn’t consider it on appeal, since it held that Medtronic
wasn’t infringing.  
 The patent relates to a heart valve mounted on a
cylindrical stent that can collapse and expand. Jacob ruled that
“cylindrical” in the patent implied the stent should have a
consistent diameter. Medtronic’s stent flares at one end.  
 Monsanto Profit Drops on Competition, Corn-Seed Earnings  
 Monsanto Co. , the world’s largest seed company, posted a 45
percent drop in third-quarter  profit  as its Roundup herbicide
lost money and corn-seed earnings fell.  
 Net income declined to $384 million, or 70 cents a share,
in the three months through May from $694 million, or $1.25, a
year earlier, St. Louis-based Monsanto said yesterday in a
statement. Sales fell 6.3 percent to $2.96 billion.  
 The unit that makes glyphosate-based weedkillers including
Roundup, the world’s best-selling herbicide, lost $189 million
after Monsanto cut prices by more than half to compete with
generics. Profit from corn seed, the company’s most valuable
product, dropped 9.5 percent to $570 million on unchanged sales.  
 Increased sales of cotton and soybean seeds, helping to
make up for price cuts in Roundup. SmartStax corn and Roundup
Ready 2 Yield soybeans, Monsanto’s newest seeds, were planted on
fewer acres than the company projected and  DuPont Co. ’s Pioneer
unit gained U.S. market share. Chief Executive Officer Hugh
Grant said in April Monsanto is unlikely to meet his 2007 goal
of doubling company gross profit by 2012.  
 Corn-seed costs rose because of new product launches in the
U.S. and Brazil, Chief Financial Officer Carl Casale said on a
conference call.  
 Profit in the fiscal year through August will be $2.40 to
$2.60 a share, Monsanto said, repeating a May 27 forecast. It
also reiterated that fiscal 2011 profit will grow by “mid-
teen” percentages. Gains will come exclusively from seed sales
and genetic licenses, the company said.  
 Lower crop prices may pressure Monsanto product pricing
next year, Mark Gulley, a New York-based analyst at Soleil
Securities, said by phone.  
 SmartStax, developed with  Dow Chemical Co. , cost 17 percent
more than earlier versions of premium corn seed.  
 Monsanto will halve the premiums it charged this year for
Smartstax and Roundup Ready 2 seeds to encourage trials of the
products, Grant said. The reduction in Roundup Ready 2 comes
largely from making seed treatments optional to growers, he
said.  
 Monsanto planned to charge 42 percent more for Roundup
Ready 2 this year than the original herbicide-tolerant beans
introduced in 1996. The original beans lose patent protection in
2014, after which the company has said rivals may make generic
copies and farmers can replant saved seed containing the off-
patent technology.  
 The Justice Department is investigating whether biotech
seed patents are being abused to extend or maintain industry
dominance, according to Christine Varney, who heads the
department’s antitrust division.  
