 Trademark  
 Coach Tips Off Customs, Police in Maryland Counterfeit Case  
 Zhi Cheng Lin, the owner of a Glen Burnie, Maryland, store
where $350,000 in knockoff handbags were seized in December,
pleaded guilty to criminal trademark infringement in a Maryland
state court, the Maryland Gazette  reported .  
 The shop, Gift World, had loose Dolce & Gabana Spa, and
Jimmy Choo emblems, even though labels inside many of the purses
indicated they were made in China, and their price tags were a
fraction of the cost of the legitimate items, according to the
newspaper.  
 Law enforcement was tipped off by a shopper who called
 Coach Inc. , which then contacted both local police and U.S.
Customs and Immigration, according to the Gazette.  
 Lin, who was sentenced to pay restitution and to serve two
years’ probation, told the court through an interpreter that he
didn’t know much about U.S. law, and would never do such a thing
again, the newspaper reported.  
