 Trade Secrets/Industrial Espionage  
 Eaton’s $1.5 million Sanctions Order Stands, High Court Rules  
 Eaton Corp. ’s Eaton Aerospace unit must pay sanctions of
more than $1.5 million after Mississippi’s Supreme Court
confirmed a lower court’s order, the Clarion-Ledger  reported .  
 The case stems from Cleveland-based Eaton’s allegations
that five former engineers took the company’s trade secrets with
them to Frisby Aerospace, according to the newspaper.  
 The sanctions were for deliberately not providing records,
the newspaper reported.  
 Many of the court records are sealed, and counsel for both
sides declined to discuss further the case that also contained
allegations that Hinds County Circuit Judge Bobby Delaughter
improperly influenced by an Eaton employee, according to the
Clarion-Ledger.  
 Trade Secrets Fee Award Not Dischargeable, Bankruptcy Court Says  
 An attorney-fee award in a trade secrets case is
enforceable, even in a bankruptcy, a bankruptcy judge in Hawaii
ruled.  
 A California state court ruled in 2007 that Nicole Marie
Snegosky took trade secrets from San Francisco’s  Research Data
Group Inc.  and brought them to a competitor,  Zach’s Investment
Research Inc.  of Chicago.  
 A 2008 settlement agreement reduced the judgment to
$350,000 to be paid in installments. Snegosky then filed a
bankruptcy petition and argued that the judgment shouldn’t be
enforced.  
 Research Data Group claimed she should still have to pay
the judgment even after her bankruptcy filing.  
 Judge Robert J. Faris agreed. In his June 29 ruling, he
said that bankruptcy law says debts for fraud, embezzlement or
larceny can’t be discharged.  
 He then looked at California state law and determined that
Snegosky’s trade-secret misappropriation could be considered
larceny and embezzlement, and that she acted willfully and
maliciously.  
 He said he will issue a separate ruling determining that
all the claims made by her former employer can’t be eliminated
by the bankruptcy filing.  
 Research Data Group was represented by  Gregory W. Kugle  of
Honolulu’s  Damon Key Leong Kupchak Hastert ;   William A. Logan 
Jr. of Walnut Creek, California-based  Logan & Giles LLP  and Todd
Y. Hirai of Honolulu.  
 Snegosky was represented by Bradley R. Tamm,  Lissa D.
Shults  and Seth K. Weaver of  Shults & Tamm ALC , and Stuart T.
Ing of the  Law Office of Stuart T. Ing , all of Honolulu.  
 The case is Research Data Group Inc. v. Snegosky, 09-90013,
U.S. Bankruptcy Court, District of Hawaii (Honolulu).  
